  "prompt": "What is Electromagnetic spectrum?",
  "response": "The electromagnetic spectrum is the range of all types of electromagnetic radiation. Electromagnetic radiation refers to the waves of the electromagnetic field, propagating through space and carrying electromagnetic radiant energy. The electromagnetic spectrum encompasses wavelengths and frequencies from the lowest to the highest.\n\nHere are the main categories of the electromagnetic spectrum, ordered from the longest wavelength (lowest frequency) to the shortest wavelength (highest frequency):\n\n1. **Radio Waves**: These have the longest wavelengths, ranging from about 1 millimeter to 100 kilometers, and are used primarily for communication such as television, radio, and cell phones.\n\n2. **Microwaves**: With wavelengths ranging from about 1 millimeter to 1 meter, microwaves are used in radar technology, as well as in microwave ovens to heat food.\n\n3. **Infrared (IR) Radiation**: Infrared waves have wavelengths ranging from approximately 700 nanometers to 1 millimeter. They are commonly associated with heat and are used in thermal imaging, night-vision equipment, and remote controls.\n\n4. **Visible Light**: Visible light consists of wavelengths that the human eye is sensitive to, ranging from about 400 nanometers (violet) to 700 nanometers (red). This range is what we perceive as colors.\n\n5. **Ultraviolet (UV) Radiation**: UV radiation ranges from about 10 to 400 nanometers. It is responsible for sunburns and is used in black lights and sterilization processes.\n\n6. **X-rays**: X-rays have wavelengths ranging from 0.01 to 10 nanometers. They are commonly used in medical imaging to view the inside of the body.\n\n7. **Gamma Rays**: Gamma rays have the shortest wavelengths, less than 0.01 nanometers, and the highest frequencies. They are produced by radioactive atoms and nuclear explosions and are used in cancer treatment and various forms of high-energy astronomical observations.\n\nEach type of electromagnetic radiation has its own set of properties and uses based on its wavelength and frequency. The electromagnetic spectrum is fundamental to many fields including astronomy, medicine, communications, and various technologies.",
